<h1 class="rm-manual">Gems market in Chanthaburi closed for 14 days</h1>
<ul class="rm-manual"> <li class="rm-manual">May 8, 2021</li> <li class="rm-manual"><p class="rm-manual"> <span>views </span> <span>1,596</span> </p></li> </ul>
<p class="rm-manual">File Photo</p>
<p>The famous Gems Market, or Gems Road, in Thailand’s the eastern 
province of Chanthaburi has been ordered to close for 14 days, after a 
group of 52 African gem traders were found to be infected with COVID-19.</p>
<p>Dr. Apirak Pisut-arporn, the provincial health chief, said Friday 
that this cluster of infections has affected a large group of people, 
hence the need to conduct active screening among all the Africans in the
 province and other people in their communities.</p>
<p>The infected have been sent to hospitals for treatment, while those 
who were in close contact with them have been placed in isolation and 
under observation.</p>
<p>Governor Suthee Thongyaem also expressed concern that the infected 
African gem traders might have spread the disease among Muslims in the 
province, because they are also Muslims and pray at the Mosque during 
the fasting month of the Ramadan.</p>
<p class="rm-manual">He said those who attended prayers at the mosque 
will be asked to report for COVID-19 screening quickly, to prevent the 
further spread of the disease.</p>
